definition.value: The gender with which a person identifies.
Any of various gender identities which occur in a specific cultural context outside of a binary gender system.

This term (and its forerunner "third gender" and its variants) may be considered colonialistic and Eurocentric depending on the context. It may be better to list specific gender identities instead; or to simply allow for a person to self-identify in a free-text space.
A datum representing that a person's gender identity is not known for any of various reasons.
A datum representing when an individual does not wish to disclose their gender identity, thereby making their gender identity unknown.

A datum representing a person's gender identity which is not listed. Note that it is generally considered inappropriate to list "other" instead of including some nonbinary options. However, an "other (please specify)" should always be included for the sake of completeness.

An indication that no gender identity has developed; use for neonates whose assigned sex at birth is "undifferentiated". For a person who identifies as not having a gender, use "non-gendered identity".
An assignment of an "X" gender shortly after birth. Note that "X" is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates.
Use in situations where no gender was assigned at birth; i.e. no birth certificate was issued shortly after birth or no birth certificate gender was recorded.

An assignment of an intersex gender marker shortly after birth. Note that "intersex" is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates. Further, note that "intersex" itself is not a gender, but is a legal gender in this context.
Circumcision during adulthood.
Circumcision of an infant, typically an individual under one year of age.
Circumcision of the penis during infanthood.
Circumcision during childhood.
Circumcision of the penis during childhood.
A type of erotic dance performance offered in some strip clubs in which the dancer typically has body contact with a seated patron.
An erotic dance performed at (or on) a table or bar, as opposed to on a stage.
Events pertaining to given aspects of film.
Events pertaining to a variety of kinds of arts, although typically focusing on performing arts.

An entertainment show made up of a variety of acts including musical performances, sketch comedy, magic, acrobatics, juggling, and ventriloquism. It is normally introduced by a comp√®re (master of ceremonies) or host.

A kind of variety show derived from elements of Victorian burlesque, music hall and minstrel shows. Burlesque shows in America became popular in the late 1860s and slowly evolved to feature ribald comedy and female nudity. By the early 1930s the striptease element of burlesque overshadowed the comedy and subjected burlesque to extensive local legislation. Burlesque gradually lost popularity beginning in the 1940s. A number of producers sought to capitalize on nostalgia for the entertainment by attempting to recreate the spirit of burlesque in Hollywood films from the 1930s to the 1960s. There has been a resurgence of interest in this format since the 1990s.

A kind of variety show featuring music, song, dance, recitation, or drama. It is mainly distinguished by the performance venue, which might be a pub, a casino, a hotel, a restaurant, or a nightclub with a stage for performances. The audience, often dining or drinking, does not typically dance but usually sits at tables. Performances are usually introduced by a master of ceremonies or MC.
A theatrical genre involving elements derived from Victorian burlesque, music hall and minstrel shows.

A form of theatrical entertainment featuring music, song, dance, recitation, or drama. It is mainly distinguished by the performance venue, which might be a pub, a casino, a hotel, a restaurant, or a nightclub with a stage for performances. The audience, often dining or drinking, does not typically dance but usually sits at tables. Performances are usually introduced by a master of ceremonies or MC. The entertainment, as done by an ensemble of actors and according to its European origins, is often (but not always) oriented towards adult audiences and of a clearly underground nature. In the United States striptease, burlesque, drag shows, or a solo vocalist with a pianist, as well as the venues which offer this entertainment, are often advertised as cabarets.

A theatrical genre derived from elements of Victorian burlesque, music hall and minstrel shows. Burlesque in America became popular in the late 1860s and slowly evolved to feature ribald comedy and female nudity. By the early 1930s the striptease element of burlesque overshadowed the comedy and subjected burlesque to extensive local legislation. Burlesque gradually lost popularity beginning in the 1940s. A number of producers sought to capitalize on nostalgia for the entertainment by attempting to recreate the spirit of burlesque in Hollywood films from the 1930s to the 1960s. There has been a resurgence of interest in this format since the 1990s.

The revival and updating of the traditional American burlesque performance. Though based on the traditional burlesque art, the new form encompasses a wider range of performance styles; neo-burlesque acts can range from anything from classic striptease to modern dance to theatrical mini-dramas to comedic mayhem.

Neo-burlesque shows that feature male-body roles have been dubbed as boylesque. The introduction of boylesque elements can be seen as a key difference between neo-burlesque and earlier, exclusively female-body forms of burlesque, which sometimes incorporated drag-queen roles (i.e. male impersonators of female bodies) but did not directly represent masculinity. Boylesque within the neo-burlesque scene can be traced back to the early 1980s with performers like John Sex.
An assignment of an "other" gender marker shortly after birth. Note that "other" is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates.
Refers to either (1) femininity as expressed by travestis; or (2) an official legal transfeminine non-binary gender marker allowed through judicial ruling in 2019.

An assignment of an indeterminate gender marker shortly after birth. Note that "indeterminate" is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates. Further, note that "indeterminate" itself is not a gender, but is a legal gender in this context.
An assignment of a nonbinary gender shortly after birth. Note that "nonbinary" is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates.
An assignment of an "U" gender shortly after birth. Note that "U" is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates.

An assignment of a diverse gender marker shortly after birth. Note that "diverse" is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates. Further, note that "diverse" itself is not a gender, but is a legal gender in this context.

An assignment of a "eunuch" gender marker shortly after birth. Note that "eunuch" is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates. Further, note that "eunuch" itself is not a gender, but is a legal gender in this context. This term may also be offensive depending on the context.

An assignment of a "third gender" gender marker shortly after birth. Note that "third gender" is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates. Further, note that "third gender" itself is not a gender, but is a legal gender in this context. This term may also be offensive depending on the context.
An assignment of an "unspecified" gender shortly after birth. Note that "unspecified" is only available in certain jurisdictions on birth certificates.

A gender (or gender marker) assigned to an individual by themselves as part of the right to self-determination. Note that not all jurisdictions allow for updating of assigned gender at birth (AGAB). Typically, in practice, this represents the gender marker on the most recent or most up-to-date birth certificate for an intersex, transgender, and/or nonbinary person, aside from their original birth certificate (or certification of birth).
A birth certificate which has been amended for any of various reasons.

A type of birth certificate allowed if the birth occurred at a person's home or house. Home birth certificates often require different registration processes and may not be available in all jurisdictions.
A certificate which documents a particular individual's citizenship status.

A type of birth certificate which typically includes name, place and date of birth, parental information, date of issue, date of registration, registration number, certificate number, and authorised signature(s). Not available in all jurisdictions.

A type of birth certificate which typically includes name, place and date of birth, date of issue, date of registration, registration number, certificate number, and authorised signature(s). Not available in all jurisdictions.

A type of Quebec birth certificated issued with regard to a birth that occurred outside of Quebec, under paragraph 137 of the Civil Code of Qu√©bec, until their full authenticity is recognized by a Quebec court.

A type of birth certificate issued from 1963 until November 1979 by the Department of National Defense in Canada to dependents of Canadian Forces members born overseas. These certificates were never accorded legal status, but served as a convenient substitute for the original record of birth from the country of birth. Today, the DND 419 is recognised as a proof of age, but not of citizenship.
A birth certificate issued by a public notary by way of presenting supporting documents.
A birth certificate issued in a medical context.
A type of birth certificate issued to persons born in Denmark and baptized in the Church of Denmark.
A type of birth certificate issued to persons born in Denmark and not baptized in the Church of Denmark.
A birth certificate originating in a foreign country (often as opposed to country of residence).
A type of birth certificate issued to Indonesian-born individuals, per the Denpasar Civil Registry.
A type of birth certificate issued to Indonesian-born individuals, per the Denpasar Civil Registry.
